solution.p:
We write the piecewise definition of \abs{3x - 6}.
\abs{3x-6} = \begin{cases} 3x-6 \amp \text{if } 3x-6\ge 0 \text{, or } x\ge 2\\ -(3x-6) \amp \text{if } 3x - 6\lt 0 \text{, or }x\lt 2 \end{cases}
Thus, the absolute value equation \abs{3x - 6} = 9 is equivalent to two regular equations: 3x - 6 =9~~~ \text{ or }~~~ -(3x - 6) = 9 or, by simplifying the second equation, 3x - 6 =9~~~ \text{ or }~~~ 3x - 6 = -9 Solving these two equations gives us the same solutions we found in , namely x = 5 and -1.

First, we solve the equation ~\abs{4x - 15} = 0.01. There are two cases:
\begin{aligned}[t] 4x - 15 \amp = 0.01 \amp \text{or} \amp\amp 4x - 15 \amp= -0.01 \\ 4x \amp = 15.01 \amp\amp\amp 4x \amp = 14.99 \\ x \amp = 3.7525 \amp\amp\amp x \amp= 3.7475 \end{aligned}
Because the inequality symbol is \lt, the solutions of the inequality are between these two values: 3.7475 \lt x \lt 3.7525. In interval notation, the solutions are (3.7475, 3.7525).

li.p:
Let x represent the number of miles on the highway and f (x) the number of miles from the mall. For x-values less than 15, the graph is a straight line with slope -1 and y-intercept at (0, 15), so its equation is y = -x + 15. Thus, f (x) = -x + 15~~~ \text{ when } ~~~0 \le x \lt 15 On the other hand, when x \ge 15, the graph of f is a straight line with slope 1 that passes through the point (15, 0). The point-slope form of this line is y = 0 + 1(x - 15) so y = x - 15. Thus, f (x) = x - 15~~~ \text{ when }~~~ x \ge 15 Combining the two pieces, we obtain
f (x) = \begin{cases} -x + 15~~~ \amp \text{when }~~~ 0\le x\lt 15\\ x - 15~~~ \amp \text{when }~~~ x\ge 15 \end{cases}
The graph of f (x) is a part of the graph of y = \abs{x - 15}. If we think of the highway as a portion of the real number line, with Marlene’s on-ramp located at the origin, then the outlet mall is located at 15. Marlene's coordinate as she drives along the highway is x, and the distance from Marlene to the mall is given by f (x) = \abs{x - 15}.

